              "displayName": "Jun Gong",
              "active": true,
              "timeZone": "Asia/Shanghai"
            },
            "body": "[~junping_du] Thank you for the comment and suggestion.\n\nbq. Can we just set \"yarn.resourcemanager.connect.max-wait.ms\" to some larger value than 900 seconds? \n\nA larger value might lead to another problem. When a network partition causes some NM could not heartbeat with RM, these NM must kill containers running on it. If not, RM will complete containers running on them and notify corresponding AM  when their RMNode transition to LOST state. And AM will launch another instance doing same things. Then there will be multiple instance problem. \n\nbq. YARN admin could make mistake that forget to set flag back, in that case applications and containers could pending forever. So whatever ways, we need a timeout here (to get rid of fault operation). \n\nYes, YARN admin might make mistake. We could workaround it as following: when setting flag, create an ephemeral znode and wait for RM to come back. The znode will disappear when admin terminate the setting process. IMO it might be more clear using 'set' and 'clear' flag.  \n\nbq. So whatever ways, we need a timeout here (to get rid of fault operation). For your concrete scenario, one interesting topic is we may allow admin to extend the timeout when cluster is on the fly. Probably, through ZKNode because RM is unavailable but that could bring extra configuration complexity.\n\nIf we set a larger timeout on the fly, we will also need set it back. I think it is same as set/clear.",
            "updateAuthor": {
              "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=johna",
              "name": "johna",
              "key": "banjo",
              "avatarUrls": {
